      "id": "ai-lab--live-system",
      "page": "ai-lab/index.html",
      "page_title": "AI Lab",
      "anchor": "live-system",
      "title": "AI Portfolio Assistant — the first Neo Labs proof.",
      "text": "Live system · real site feature The chat assistant in the corner of this site is the case study. It is a real deployed feature — not a client project, not an enterprise product, and not a fictional demo. It proves the first layer: useful AI UX connected to a secure server-side backend with honest fallback behavior. A static portfolio needed a genuinely helpful assistant without exposing an API key in browser code, saving visitor messages in the frontend, or making fake claims about clients, prices, credentials, or results. A Vercel serverless /api/chat endpoint that reads the key from server-side environment variables, with a rule-based browser fallback, backend health checks, and a validated routing layer for every link the assistant offers. Same-origin browser calls, deployment previews, and function logs make the backend testable without putting keys in GitHub Pages. Environment variables stay server-side. Replies are sanitized, routes are whitelisted, and errors return safe fallback hints. Next proof targets include prompt regression tests, model evaluation, cost/latency tracking, and monitoring for fallback behavior. Request flow Engineering decisions API key in server-side environment variables only — never in HTML, CSS, or JS. Browser talks to a same-origin /api/chat; it never calls a provider URL directly. GitHub Pages stays fallback-only — it cannot run the backend, so it degrades honestly. Vercel backend powers real model mode behind the private key. Route whitelist — assistant buttons can only link to known internal pages. Prompt constraints fix prices ($150 / $300 / $50 mo), forbid invented claims, and keep demos labeled fictional. Reply sanitizer strips placeholder # links and any invented external URLs. The UI never claims a model answered unless a real reply actually returned. Secret scans are part of the release checklist before AI changes ship. Health check & states What this proves I can connect a real product UI to a backend AI service without leaking secrets. I can design graceful degradation so the feature never lies about its state. I can add guardrails (route whitelist, prompt rules, sanitizer) to keep output safe. I can debug a live deployment from Vercel logs and explain the tradeoffs in plain English. I can separate shipped proof from planned ML/MLOps work without pretending the roadmap is already complete.",
      "chars": 2374,
      "content_sha1": "7155ed715a73"
