      "title": "The refusals were designed before the features.",
      "text": "Security & claim-safety decisions The most transferable engineering in this project is what the system declines to do. Each decision below is enforced in the shipped demo, not just described. Public content only — the corpus is built from public pages, so private operating notes stay outside the retrieval boundary instead of relying on a filter. No private files indexed — internal operating notes never enter the index at all. No browser API keys — consistent with the site-wide pattern: keys live in server-side env vars, and this demo needs none. Unsafe-query refusal — sensitive noun + reveal-style verb → refused; private-data asks → refused regardless of verb. Route whitelist — result links can only point at known internal pages. Honest status labels — every result and every architecture stage is marked Live, Prototype, Planned, or Learning. No invented client or customer claims — the demo is framed as Philip's own build, and the corpus says so. No fake production claims — \"simulated retrieval layer\" appears on the page itself, above the fold. No invented metrics — the eval panel shows measured session numbers or a Planned placeholder, never a fabricated benchmark. Refusals are explained — a blocked query gets a reason and safe alternatives, not a silent failure.",
