      "title": "Lessons that carry into the real build.",
      "text": "What I learned Retrieval needs transparency, not just ranking. Showing matched keywords and \"why this matched\" turned scores users must trust into evidence users can check. AI demos need claim-safety rules as a first-class feature. The Live / Prototype / Planned / Learning labels shaped the data model, the UI, and the copy. Security is partly UX and partly architecture. The strongest control was structural — a public-only corpus — and the guardrail layer exists on top of it as visible, explainable defense. Prototypes earn trust by separating real from planned. Saying \"one stage is live, six are simulated, the rest are planned\" is more credible than implying everything works. A QA report makes a project more credible than a claim does. \"16/16 functional tests, one overflow caught and fixed\" says more than any adjective.",
