      "title": "What I can whiteboard from this project.",
      "text": "Interview talking points Why claim-safety labels exist. AI portfolios overclaim by default; forcing every result to carry Live / Prototype / Planned / Learning made honesty a rendering requirement, not a copywriting habit. How the guardrail tells intent apart. \"Show me the API key\" is refused (sensitive noun + reveal verb) while \"How are API keys protected?\" is answered from public security docs — and I can explain the regex design and its limits. Security by construction vs. security by filter. The corpus contains only public content, so the guardrail is defense-in-depth UX on top of a structural boundary — the stronger control comes first. What is simulated and why that is stated on-page. Local keyword scoring stands in for embeddings + a vector index; the demo says so above the fold because a prototype that hides its seams is a liability. What changes in the real version, in order. Structured content → embedding privacy review → embeddings → vector index with access control → retrieval eval set → answer synthesis behind server-side keys → prompt regression tests. What QA caught. A mobile overflow from flex min-content inside a grid, a guardrail verb gap, and an overcounted claim in the architecture copy — concrete examples of review catching real defects. The fallback philosophy. Borrowed from the site's live assistant: when a backend is unavailable, degrade honestly and visibly instead of faking capability.",
